# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canonical-books
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] Martin has authored many books and magazine articles.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] He was the editor-in-chief of *C++ Report* magazine and served as the first chairman of the Agile Alliance.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] Martin joined the software industry at age 17 and is self-taught.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] In 1991, Martin founded Object Mentor, now defunct, which provided instructor-led training on the extreme programming methodology.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] As of November 2023, he operated Uncle Bob Consulting, which provides consulting and training services.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] He serves as Master Craftsman / Mentor at *Clean Coders,* a company run by his son Micah Martin, and produces training videos.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] In a 2024 interview Martin stated that he is programming primarily with Clojure.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] Martin is a proponent of software craftsmanship, agile software development, and test-driven development.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] He is credited with introducing the collection of object-oriented programming (OOP) design principles that came to be known as SOLID.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] Notable guests of his video channel include Grady Booch and Ward Cunningham.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] One term that is connected with Robert Martin is "Clean Code".
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] It is the name of a book that he wrote, a firm that he owns, a class that he teaches, and a software paradigm that he supports.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] The software paradigm involves SOLID, Test Driven Development, Keep It Simple Stupid, Structured Programming, Object Oriented Programming, and certain Design Patterns.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] A core teaching from Clean Code reads "Functions should do one thing.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] They should only do it." Martin tells how impressed he was by a program by Kent Beck: "Every function [..] was just two, or three, or four lines long.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] And each led you to the next in a compelling order.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] John Ousterhout disagrees with this advice: "once a function gets down to a few dozen lines, further reductions in size are unlikely to have much impact on readability. [..] More functions means more interfaces to document and learn.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] If functions are made too small, they lose their independence [..]" For Ousterhout, functions and other modules should be "deep", but have a small interface.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] Ousterhout also disagreed with Martin's advice against code comments, and for test-driven development.
[src:canonical-books/clean-code] Martin and Ousterhout discussed these points of disagreement and clarified their views in a long dialogue.
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] McConnell defines the main activities in software construction as detailed design, construction planning, coding and debugging, unit testing, integration and integration testing.
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] Although he does not dismiss the value of other aspects of software development such as requirements and documentation, McConnell emphasises the construction of software due to several reasons.
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] Lastly, the book contends that construction is the exclusive activity which is guaranteed to remain completed.
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] The techniques of a good programmer are also given throughout the book.
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] The whole part seven of the book is about software craftsmanship (layout, style, character, themes and self-documentation).
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] The other six parts of the book are: laying the foundation, creating high-quality code, variables, statements, code improvements and system considerations.
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] There are also negative reviews about the length and style of the book, which runs to over 900 pages and goes into detail on many topics.
[src:canonical-books/code-complete] The first edition has been superseded by *Code Complete 2*.
[src:canonical-books/compilers-principles-techniques-and-tools] It is known as the ***Dragon Book*** to generations of computer scientists as its cover depicts a knight and a dragon in battle, a metaphor for conquering complexity.
[src:canonical-books/compilers-principles-techniques-and-tools] This name can also refer to Aho and Ullman's older *Principles of Compiler Design*.
[src:canonical-books/compilers-principles-techniques-and-tools] The first edition (1986) is informally called the "red dragon book" to distinguish it from the second edition and from Aho and Ullman's 1977 *Principles of Compiler Design* sometimes known as the "green dragon book".
[src:canonical-books/compilers-principles-techniques-and-tools] Following in the tradition of its two predecessors, the second edition (2006) features a dragon and a knight on its cover, and is informally known as the **purple dragon**.
[src:canonical-books/compilers-principles-techniques-and-tools] Lam of Stanford University became a co-author with this edition.
[src:canonical-books/compilers-principles-techniques-and-tools] In order to cover recent developments and issues, there is an updated second edition from Pearson Education India (4 July 2023), with contributions from Sorav Bansal.
[src:canonical-books/compilers-principles-techniques-and-tools] This revised and updated edition has new chapters on programming language semantics and undefined behaviour semantics.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] It has been influential to the field of software engineering and is regarded as an important source for object-oriented design theory and practice.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] More than 500,000 copies have been sold in English and in 13 other languages.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Both the authors and the book are often referred to as the *Gang of Four* (GoF).
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The book started at a birds-of-a-feather session at the 1990 OOPSLA meeting, "Towards an Architecture Handbook", where Erich Gamma and Richard Helm met and discovered their common interest.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] They were later joined by Ralph Johnson and John Vlissides.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The book was originally published on 21 October 1994, with a 1995 copyright, and was made available to the public at the 1994 OOPSLA meeting.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Use of an interface also leads to dynamic binding and polymorphism, which are central features of object-oriented programming.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The authors refer to inheritance as *white-box reuse*, with white-box referring to visibility, because the internals of parent classes are often visible to subclasses.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] In contrast, the authors refer to object composition (in which objects with well-defined interfaces are used dynamically at runtime by objects obtaining references to other objects) as *black-box reuse* because no internal details of composed objects need be visible in the code using them.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The authors discuss the tension between inheritance and encapsulation at length and state that in their experience, designers overuse inheritance (Gang of Four 1995:20).
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] to details of its parent's implementation, it's often said that 'inheritance breaks encapsulation'".
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] They warn that the implementation of a subclass can become so bound up with the implementation of its parent class that any change in the parent's implementation will force the subclass to change.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Furthermore, they claim that a way to avoid this is to inherit only from abstract classes—but then, they point out that there is minimal code reuse.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Using inheritance is recommended mainly when adding to the functionality of existing components, reusing most of the old code and adding relatively small amounts of new code.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] To the authors, 'delegation' is an extreme form of object composition that can always be used to replace inheritance.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Delegation involves two objects: a 'sender' passes itself to a 'delegate' to let the delegate refer to the sender.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Thus the link between two parts of a system are established only at runtime, not at compile-time.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The Callback article has more information about delegation.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The authors also discuss so-called parameterized types, which are also known as generics (Ada, Eiffel, Java, C#, Visual Basic (.NET), and Delphi) or templates (C++).
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] These allow any type to be defined without specifying all the other types it uses—the unspecified types are supplied as 'parameters' at the point of use.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The authors further distinguish between 'Aggregation', where one object 'has' or 'is part of' another object (implying that an aggregate object and its owner have identical lifetimes) and acquaintance, where one object merely 'knows of' another object.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Sometimes acquaintance is called 'association' or the 'using' relationship.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Acquaintance objects may request operations of each other, but they are not responsible for each other.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Acquaintance is a weaker relationship than aggregation and suggests much looser coupling between objects, which can often be desirable for maximum maintainability in designs.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] The authors employ the term 'toolkit' where others might today use 'class library', as in C# or Java.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] In their parlance, toolkits are the object-oriented equivalent of subroutine libraries, whereas a 'framework' is a set of cooperating classes that make up a reusable design for a specific class of software.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] They state that applications are hard to design, toolkits are harder, and frameworks are the hardest to design.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Creational patterns are ones that create objects, rather than having to instantiate objects directly.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] This gives the program more flexibility in deciding which objects need to be created for a given case.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Structural patterns concern class and object composition.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] They use inheritance to compose interfaces and define ways to compose objects to obtain new functionality.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Most behavioral design patterns are specifically concerned with communication between objects.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] In 2005 the ACM SIGPLAN awarded that year's Programming Languages Achievement Award to the authors, in recognition of the impact of their work "on programming practice and programming language design".
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Criticism has been directed at the concept of software design patterns generally, and at *Design Patterns* specifically.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] A primary criticism of *Design Patterns* is that its patterns are simply workarounds for missing features in C++, replacing elegant abstract features with lengthy concrete patterns, essentially becoming a "human compiler".
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Peter Norvig demonstrates that 16 out of the 23 patterns in *Design Patterns* are simplified or eliminated by language features in Lisp or Dylan.
[src:canonical-books/design-patterns] Gamma wanted to remove the singleton pattern, but there was no consensus among the authors to do so.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] In the preface, the authors write about how the book was written to be comprehensive and useful in both teaching and professional environments.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] Each chapter focuses on an algorithm, and discusses its design techniques and areas of application.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] Instead of using a specific programming language, the algorithms are written in pseudocode.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] The descriptions focus on the aspects of the algorithm itself, its mathematical properties, and emphasize efficiency.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] The first edition of the textbook did not include Stein as an author, and thus the book became known by the initialism CLR.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] It included two chapters ("Arithmetic Circuits" and "Algorithms for Parallel Computers") that were dropped in the second edition.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] After the addition of the fourth author in the second edition, many began to refer to the book as "CLRS".
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] This first edition of the book was also known as "The Big White Book (of Algorithms)".
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] With the second edition, the predominant color of the cover changed to green, causing the nickname to be shortened to just "The Big Book (of Algorithms)".
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] The third edition was published in August 2009.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] The fourth edition was published in April 2022, which has colors added to improve visual presentations.
[src:canonical-books/introduction-to-algorithms] The mobile depicted on the cover, *Big Red* (1959) by Alexander Calder, can be found at the Whitney Museum of American Art in New York City.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] The authors presented most subjects as principles backed up by some concrete story or other information.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] As an example, the chapter "Spaghetti Dinner" presents a fictional example of a manager inviting a new team over for dinner, then having them buy and prepare the meal as a group, in order to produce a first team success.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] Other chapters use real-life stories or cite various studies to illustrate the principles being presented.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] The second edition kept the original content with only a few changes or corrections.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] The bulk of the new content was eight chapters in a new section at the end.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] The new section's chapters revisited some of the concepts of the original chapters with changes and added new ones.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] The eBook PDF version published by DorsetHouse was not searchable as each page appeared to be an image.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] The new content of the third edition is spread out through the book.
[src:canonical-books/peopleware-productive-projects-and-teams] There are six new chapters, but the original content has also been updated.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] MIT Press published the first edition in 1984, and the second edition in 1996.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] It was used as the textbook for MIT's introductory course in computer science from 1984 to 2007.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] SICP focuses on discovering general patterns for solving specific problems, and building software systems that make use of those patterns.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] MIT Press published a JavaScript version of the book in 2022.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] The book describes computer science concepts using Scheme, a dialect of Lisp.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] It also uses a virtual register machine and assembler to implement Lisp interpreters and compilers.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] The book is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-SA 4.0) license.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] The book was used as the textbook for MIT's former introductory programming course, 6.001, from fall 1984 through its last semester, in fall 2007.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] Other schools also made use of the book as a course textbook.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] A review of SICP as an undergraduate textbook by Philip Wadler noted the weaknesses of the Scheme language as an introductory language for a computer science course.
[src:canonical-books/structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs] SICP has been influential in computer science education, and several later books have been inspired by its style.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] When Knuth began the project in 1962, he originally conceived of it as a single book with twelve chapters.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] The first three volumes of what was then expected to be a seven-volume set were published in 1968, 1969, and 1973.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Work began in earnest on Volume 4 in 1973, but was suspended in 1977 for work on typesetting prompted by the second edition of Volume 2.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Writing of the final copy of Volume 4A began in longhand in 2001, and the first online pre-fascicle, 2A, appeared later in 2001.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] The first published installment of Volume 4 appeared in paperback as Fascicle 2 in 2005.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] The hardback Volume 4A, combining Volume 4, Fascicles 0–4, was published in 2011.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Volume 4, Fascicle 6 ("Satisfiability") was released in December 2015; Volume 4, Fascicle 5 ("Mathematical Preliminaries Redux; Backtracking; Dancing Links") was released in November 2019.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Volume 4B consists of material evolved from Fascicles 5 and 6.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] The manuscript was sent to the publisher on August 1, 2022, and the volume was published in September 2022.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Fascicle 7 ("Constraint Satisfaction"), planned for Volume 4C, was the subject of Knuth's talk on August 3, 2022 and was published on February 5, 2025.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] After winning a Westinghouse Talent Search scholarship, Knuth enrolled at the Case Institute of Technology (now Case Western Reserve University), where his performance was so outstanding that the faculty voted to award him a master of science upon his completion of the bachelor's degree.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] During his summer vacations, Knuth was hired by the Burroughs Corporation to write compilers, earning more in his summer months than full professors did for an entire year.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Such exploits made Knuth a topic of discussion among the mathematics department, which included Richard S.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] In January 1962, when he was a graduate student in the mathematics department at Caltech, Knuth was approached by Addison-Wesley to write a book about compiler design, and he proposed a larger scope.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] He came up with a list of twelve chapter titles the same day.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] In the summer of 1962 he worked on a FORTRAN compiler for UNIVAC, considering that he had "sold my soul to the devil" to develop a FORTRAN compiler after ALGOL developments with Burroughs.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] He remained as a consultant to Burroughs over the period 1960 to 1968 while writing Volume 1 "Fundamental Algorithms".
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] During this time, he also developed a mathematical analysis of linear probing, which convinced him to present the material with a quantitative approach.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] After receiving his Ph.D. in June 1963, he began working on his manuscript, of which he finished his first draft in June 1965, at 3000 hand-written pages.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] He had assumed that about five hand-written pages would translate into one printed page, but his publisher said instead that about 1+1⁄2 hand-written pages translated to one printed page.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] This meant he had approximately 2000 printed pages of material, which closely matches the size of the first three published volumes.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] The first volume of "The Art of Computer Programming", "Fundamental Algorithms", took five years to complete between 1963 and 1968 while working at both Caltech and Burroughs.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] In the preface, he thanks first his wife Jill, then Burroughs for the use of B220 and B5500 computers in testing most of the programs, and Caltech, the National Science Foundation, and the Office of Naval Research.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Section 2.5 of "Fundamental Algorithms" is on Dynamic Storage Allocation.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Parts of this are used in the Burroughs approach to memory management.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Varga, who was the scientific adviser to the publisher.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Varga was visiting Olga Taussky-Todd and John Todd at Caltech.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] With Varga's enthusiastic endorsement, the publisher accepted Knuth's expanded plans.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] In its expanded version, the book would be published in seven volumes, each with just one or two chapters.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Due to the growth in Chapter 7, which was fewer than 100 pages of the 1965 manuscript, per Vol.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] 4A p. vi, the plan for Volume 4 has since expanded to include Volumes 4A, 4B, 4C, 4D, and possibly more.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] In 1976, Knuth prepared a second edition of Volume 2, requiring it to be typeset again, but the style of type used in the first edition (called hot type) was no longer readily available.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] In 1977, he decided to spend some time creating something more suitable.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Eight years later, he returned with TEX, which is currently used for all volumes.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Another characteristic of the volumes is the variation in the difficulty of the exercises including a numerical rating varying from 0 to 50, where 0 is trivial, and 50 is an open question in contemporary research.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] All examples in the books use a hypothetical language called "MIX assembly language" (MIXAL), which runs on "a mythical computer called 'MIX,'" which was developed to be contemporaneous with other 1960s and 1970s computers.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] MMIX would reach its stable release in 2011.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Knuth considers the use of assembly language necessary for the speed and memory usage of algorithms to be judged.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Regarding the origin of MIX, Knuth remarked it was much like any computer then in existence, "but, perhaps, nicer." The name *MIX* can be represented as 1009 in Roman numerals.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Further, Knuth explains the derivation of 1009 came from taking sixteen actual computers he deemed similar to MIX and on which MIX was easily simulated.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Software such as the GNU MIX Development Kit (MDK) exists to provide emulation of the MIX architecture.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] These volumes were superseded by newer editions and are in order by date.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Volume 4, Fascicles 0–4 were revised and published as Volume 4A.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Volume 4, Fascicles 5–6 were revised and published as Volume 4B.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] Pre-fascicles contain draft of evolving material for future Fascicles.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] They are put online primarily so that experts in the field can check the contents before distributing them to a wider audience.
[src:canonical-books/the-art-of-computer-programming] The remaining pre-fascicles contain draft material that is set to appear in future fascicles and volumes.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] C was created by Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs in the early 1970s as an augmented version of Ken Thompson's B.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] Another Bell Labs employee, Brian Kernighan, had written the first C tutorial, and he persuaded Ritchie to coauthor a book on the language.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] Kernighan would write most of the book's "expository" material, and Ritchie's reference manual became its appendices.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] The first edition, published February 22, 1978, was the first widely available book on the C programming language.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] Its version of C is sometimes termed *K&R C* (after the book's authors), often to distinguish this early version from the later version of C standardized as ANSI C.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] In April 1988, the second edition of the book was published, updated to cover the changes to the language resulting from the then-new ANSI C standard, particularly with the inclusion of reference material on standard libraries.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] The second edition of the book (and as of 2024, the most recent) has since been translated into over 20 languages.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] In 2012, an eBook version of the second edition was published in ePub, Mobi, and PDF formats.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] C was first standardized in 1989 (as ANSI X3.159-1989) and has since undergone several revisions.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] However, no new edition of *The C Programming Language* has been issued to cover the more recent standards.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] The book introduced the "Hello, World!" program, which prints only the text "hello, world" as an illustration of a minimal working C program.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] Since then, many texts have followed that convention for introducing a programming language.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] Before the advent of ANSI C, the first edition of the text served as the *de facto* standard of the language for writers of C compilers.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] The influence of *The C Programming Language* on programmers, a generation of whom first worked with C in universities and industry, has led many to accept the authors' programming style and conventions as recommended practice, if not normative practice.
[src:canonical-books/the-c-programming-language] For example, the coding and formatting style of the programs presented in both editions of the book is often referred to as "K&R style" and became the coding style used by convention in the source code for the Unix and Linux kernels.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] The illustration on the cover of the book is a 1913 painting by Lyubov Popova titled *Composition with Figures* and belongs to the collection of the State Tretyakov Gallery.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] The book was released under the Open Publication License v2.0 in 1999.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] The essay's central thesis is Raymond's proposition that "given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow" (which he terms Linus's law): the more widely available the source code is for public testing, scrutiny, and experimentation, the more rapidly all forms of bugs will be discovered.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] In contrast, Raymond claims that an inordinate amount of time and energy must be spent hunting for bugs in the Cathedral model, since the working version of the code is available only to a few developers.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Great ones know what to rewrite (and reuse).
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Plan to throw one [version] away; you will, anyhow (copied from Frederick Brooks's *The Mythical Man-Month*).
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] If you have the right attitude, interesting problems will find you.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] When you lose interest in a program, your last duty to it is to hand it off to a competent successor.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Treating your users as co-developers is your least-hassle route to rapid code improvement and effective debugging.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Given a large enough beta-tester and co-developer base, almost every problem will be characterized quickly and the fix obvious to someone.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Smart data structures and dumb code works a lot better than the other way around.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] If you treat your beta-testers as if they're your most valuable resource, they will respond by becoming your most valuable resource.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] The next best thing to having good ideas is recognizing good ideas from your users.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Often, the most striking and innovative solutions come from realizing that your concept of the problem was wrong.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Perfection (in design) is achieved not when there is nothing more to add, but rather when there is nothing more to take away.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Any tool should be useful in the expected way, but a truly great tool lends itself to uses you never expected.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] When writing gateway software of any kind, take pains to disturb the data stream as little as possible—and never throw away information unless the recipient forces you to!
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] When your [configuration] language is nowhere near Turing-complete, syntactic sugar can be your friend.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] A security system is only as secure as its secret.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] To solve an interesting problem, start by finding a problem that is interesting to you.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Provided the development coordinator has a communications medium at least as good as the Internet, and knows how to lead without coercion, many heads are inevitably better than one.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] In 1998, the essay helped the final push for Netscape Communications Corporation to release the source code for Netscape Communicator and start the Mozilla project; it was cited by Frank Hecker and other employees as an outside independent validation of his arguments.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Netscape's public recognition of this influence brought Raymond renown in hacker culture.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] When O'Reilly Media published the book in 1999 it became one of the first complete, commercially distributed books published under the Open Publication License.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Marshall Poe, in his essay "The Hive", likens Wikipedia to the bazaar model that Raymond defines.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Jimmy Wales himself was inspired by the work (as well as arguments put forward in pre-Internet works, such as Friedrich Hayek's article "The Use of Knowledge in Society"), arguing that "It opened my eyes to the possibility of mass collaboration".
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] In 1999 Nikolai Bezroukov published two critical essays on Eric Raymond's views of open source software, the second one called "A second look at *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*".
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] They produced a sharp response from Eric Raymond.
[src:canonical-books/the-cathedral-and-the-bazaar] Curtis Yarvin's essay "The Cathedral or the Bizarre", which argues for the end of American democracy, is named after the Raymond essay.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Brooks's observations are based on his experiences at IBM while managing the development of OS/360.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] He had added more programmers to a project falling behind schedule, a decision that he would later conclude had, counter-intuitively, delayed the project even further.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] He also made the mistake of asserting that one project—involved in writing an ALGOL compiler—would require six months, regardless of the number of workers involved (it required longer).
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The tendency for managers to repeat such errors in project development led Brooks to quip that his book is called "The Bible of Software Engineering", because "everybody quotes it, some people read it, and a few people go by it".
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The work was first published in 1975 (ISBN 0-201-00650-2), reprinted with corrections in 1982, and republished in an anniversary edition with four extra chapters in 1995 (ISBN 0-201-83595-9), including a reprint of the essay "No Silver Bullet" with commentary by the author.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Brooks discusses several causes of scheduling failures.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The most enduring is his discussion of Brooks's law: *Adding manpower to a late software project makes it later*.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Man-month is a hypothetical unit of work representing the work done by one person in one month; Brooks's law says that the possibility of measuring useful work in man-months is a myth, and is hence the centerpiece of the book.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Complex programming projects cannot be perfectly partitioned into discrete tasks that can be worked on without communication between the workers and without establishing a set of complex interrelationships between tasks and the workers performing them.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Therefore, assigning more programmers to a project running behind schedule will make it even later.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] This is because the time required for the new programmers to learn about the project and the increased communication overhead will consume an ever-increasing quantity of the calendar time available.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] When *n* people have to communicate among themselves, as *n* increases, their output decreases and when it becomes negative the project is delayed further with every person added.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Brooks added the chapter "No Silver Bullet—Essence and Accidents in Software Engineering" and further reflections on it in the chapter "'No Silver Bullet' Refired" to the anniversary edition of *The Mythical Man-Month*.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The argument relies on the distinction between accidental complexity and essential complexity, similar to the way Amdahl's law relies on the distinction between "parallelizable" and "strictly serial".
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The second-system effect proposes that, when an architect designs a second system, it is the most dangerous system they will ever design, because they will tend to incorporate all of the additions they originally did not add to the first system due to inherent time constraints.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Thus, when embarking on a second system, an engineer should be mindful that they are susceptible to over-engineering it.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The author makes the observation that in a suitably complex system there is a certain irreducible number of errors.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Any attempt to fix observed errors tends to result in the introduction of other errors.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Brooks wrote "Question: How does a large software project get to be one year late?
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Answer: One day at a time!" Incremental slippages on many fronts eventually accumulate to produce a large overall delay.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Continued attention to meeting small individual milestones is required at each level of management.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] To make a user-friendly system, the system must have conceptual integrity, which can only be achieved by separating architecture from implementation.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] A single chief architect (or a small number of architects), acting on the user's behalf, decides what goes in the system and what stays out.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The architect or team of architects should develop an idea of what the system should do and make sure that this vision is understood by the rest of the team.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] A novel idea by someone may not be included if it does not fit seamlessly with the overall system design.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] In fact, to ensure a user-friendly system, a system may deliberately provide *fewer* features than it is capable of.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The point being, if a system is too complicated to use, many features will go unused because no one has time to learn them.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The chief architect produces a manual of system specifications.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] It should describe the external specifications of the system in detail, that is everything that the user sees.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The manual should be altered as feedback comes in from the implementation teams and the users.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] When designing a new kind of system, a team *will* design a throw-away system (whether it intends to or not).
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] This system acts as a "pilot plan" that reveals techniques that will subsequently cause a complete redesign of the system.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] This second, *smarter* system should be the one delivered to the customer, since delivery of the pilot system would cause nothing but agony to the customer, and possibly ruin the system's reputation and maybe even the company.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Every project manager should create a small core set of formal documents defining the project objectives, how they are to be achieved, who is going to achieve them, when they are going to be achieved, and how much they are going to cost.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] These documents may also reveal inconsistencies that are otherwise hard to see.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] When estimating project times, it should be remembered that programming products (which can be sold to paying customers) and programming systems are both three times as hard to write as simple independent in-house programs.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] It should be kept in mind how much of the work week will actually be spent on technical issues, as opposed to administrative or other non-technical tasks, such as meetings, and especially "stand-up" or "all-hands" meetings.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] To avoid disaster, all the teams working on a project should remain in contact with each other in as many ways as possible (e-mail, phone, meetings, memos, etc.).
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Instead of assuming something, implementers should ask the architect(s) to clarify their intent on a feature they are implementing, before proceeding with an assumption that might very well be completely incorrect.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The architect(s) are responsible for formulating a group picture of the project and communicating it to others.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Additionally, Brooks muses that "good" programmers are generally five to ten times as productive as mediocre ones.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Therefore, many things only become apparent once a certain amount of work has been done on a new system, allowing a user to experience it.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] This experience will yield insights, which will change a user's needs or the perception of the user's needs.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] The system should, therefore, be changed to fulfill the changed requirements of the user.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] This can only occur up to a certain point, otherwise the system may never be completed.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] At a certain date, no more changes should be allowed to the system and the code should be frozen.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] All requests for changes should be delayed until the *next* version of the system.
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] Instead of every programmer having their own special set of tools, each team should have a designated tool-maker who may create tools that are highly customized for the job that team is doing (e.g. a code generator tool that creates code based on a specification).
[src:canonical-books/the-mythical-man-month] In addition, system-wide tools should be built by a common tools team, overseen by the project manager.
[src:canonical-books/the-pragmatic-programmer] The book does not present a systematic theory, but rather a collection of tips to improve the development process in a pragmatic way.
[src:canonical-books/the-pragmatic-programmer] The main qualities of what the authors refer to as a pragmatic programmer are early adoption, fast adaptation, inquisitiveness and critical thinking, realism, and being a jack-of-all-trade.
[src:canonical-books/the-pragmatic-programmer] The book uses analogies and short stories to present development methodologies and caveats, for example the broken windows theory, the story of the stone soup, or the boiling frog.
[src:canonical-books/the-pragmatic-programmer] Some concepts were named or popularized in the book, such as DRY (or *don't repeat yourself*) and rubber duck debugging, a method of debugging whose name is a reference to a story in the book.
